Question: How do you believe ACME should better support organizations and cultural leaders?

Response ID: resp_592
Response Text: The change in City of Austin Cultural funding occurred at least three years ago after an extensive project to review cultural funding.  As a result many organizations were passed over for funding--many of organizations had been funded for over 20 years--and suddenly they don't meet funding criteria.  The application for funding focused on diversity, equity and inclusion and was similar to a social services funding application.  The interview team knew nothing about the music our organization performs (early music-classical), and deemed that we did not meet the funding requirements and deemed us to be elitist. There was no consideration of performance quality, diversity of performers and musicians, and length of service to the Austin Community.  It was very dispiriting and demeaning to our mission and prior performances.  Almost all of the Austin classical music organizations were cut from funding.  How is that equitable?  After all the study and work I can't believe that the mission of the cultural arts program was to cut funding for classical music in Austin.  We are one of the few surviving organizations, Texas Early Music Project.  We continue to be funded by Texas Commission on the Arts and our very generous donors.  But the City of Austin is not among them.

